@Don Killuminati Let me dumb this down for you. The earth's average temperature began rising at a MUCH faster rate than ANY cyclic, normal climatic shifts after the Industrial Revolution. That sun warming shit you're babbling about is complete nonsense. The sun changes temperature and luminosity very slowly and has a negligible affect on the short-term climate change we're experiencing. We have thown off the balance of greenhouse gasses by pumping it into the air. The carbon dioxide we're releasing into the atmosphere is a great absorber of radiation in the infared spectrum. This prevents the Earth from cooling properly, as the primary way the Earth cools is by radiating infared waves. This is similar to how a greenhouse works, thus their names. Water vapor is also a very effective greenhouse gas. Warmer seas and air mean more water vapor. If you were to look at a temperature graph of the Earth over thousands and thousands of years, you would see large, sprawling temperature fluctuations over very long periods of time. Currently, the Earth's average temperature is rising at an exponentially faster rate than what is normal over the past millions of years, and it started when we began releasing greenhouse gases. So, no. Climate change is not a "hoax". Yes. It is caused by humans, and no. You are not very smart, so stop acting like it.

You people on here freaking out about this have serious mental issues.¬† You are incapable of logic, nothing but pure, hysterical emotions.¬† Let's look at the facts for a few minutes:¬† First, I actually listened to President Trump's speech, and I have also read for myself some of the conditions of the Paris climate agreement.¬† Trump did not, at any point, deny the issue of climate change, nor did he say that he or the USA did not care about the issue.¬† He stated repeatedly that he is¬†open to the idea of either coming up with a new agreement that is fair to the U.S. and is also actually effective, or renegotiating the current one.¬† FYI, the Paris agreement will lower the temperature less than two tenths of one degree Celcius by the year 2100.¬† That is insignificant and really does nothing at all to stop global warming.¬† If you are going to have an agreement, come up with one that actually works, and don't tell me that its better than nothing, because when you consider the cost, its worse than if we do nothing.¬†¬†The agreement also penalizes the USA economically, stunting our own growth while forcing the¬†global redistribution of wealth from the USA to 'developing nations'.¬† This is not only at the expense of the American people, but two of these¬†'developing nations' are not only the biggest polluters on the planet, but they (China and India) are free to do pretty much whatever they want for the next decade.¬† Why in the hell would we be giving money to China?¬† They are not a poor country:¬† Their economy¬†will soon overtake ours.¬† They have a huge, modern military, a space program, etc...¬† Why should we be part of any agreement that hands them so much as one dime of U.S. taxpayers' money?¬† Trump was absolutely right to pull out of an unfair, ineffective treaty, and the only reason the Eurotrash and the rest of the signers of this agreement are so upset is that they no longer get a free ride at our expense.¬† Under the agreement, our own energy costs would have skyrocketed to the point that we would have had power outages, and many people would have found themselves unable to pay to heat or cool their own homes.¬† Do you think people outside this country should be able to dictate this to us?¬† Thank God we have a man like Trump that actually puts America first.¬† Obama's signature into this agreement, one that came at the expense of the American people, was treasonous.¬† So, rant and rave, call me a 'denier' all you want:¬† I just know a bad deal when I see it, and so does our President.

There are literally thousands of peer reviewed scientific papers which have evidence to show the climate is warming. It doesn't take much inductive reasoning to see that atmospheric temperature and co2 concentration are closely linked and therefore humans releasing huge amounts of co2 and methane are largely to blame. With ice core records we can see concentrations of co2 going back 600,000 years. The fact that March this year marked the point when co2 went over 400 parts per million in the atmosphere should cause alarm when you look at how outlandish that figure is when checking historic records. I really cannot understand why anyone who has access to an education and the internet could ignore this data. A conspiracy is impossible with peer-reviewing because scientists are constantly competing with one another to test whether others' data is sound through scrutiny of their methods and its repeatability. If you're in any doubt about climate change I would like to know how you answer this...

In the past 'more than 10 years', there has been legislation passed by many countries to combat climate change. This legislation has helped to defend the status quo (by slowing down the rate of global warming, hence the lack of immediate destruction).

However, worldwide (not just in the area around your waterfront property), there has been a mean rise in global sea levels over the past 20 years. Want proof from someone who isn't Al Gore (even though I don't get my facts from Al Gore)? Here you go. https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/global-warming/sea-level-rise/

More than 10 years ago, Al Gore told all of us that global warming would have devastating results and cause the world's oceans to rise precipitously... Curiously, I have lived happily on waterfront property here on the Gulf Coast of¬†Florida for more than 30 years now --- but --- we haven't seen ANY rise in the Gulf water level. How weird is it that in spite of Gore's claims NOT coming true, stupid people like you are still beating the "Climate Change" dead horse... What will it take to convince you that Gore is totally wrong? http://www.investors.com/politics/commentary/al-gore-has-made-another-science-fiction-movie-about-global-warming/

And do I live in a country which benefitted economically from America being in this? No, I do not.

However, the environmental impacts of Trump pulling out of this will affect every single human being on the planet (in and outside the USA) negatively. Whilst you may argue that the agreement wouldn't cause much of a decrease in global temperatures, the main benefit from the agreement was that it would limit potential increases in global temperatures, which would prevent the issue of global warming becoming much worse than it already is.

However, as the USA is now free to pollute however it wants, it means that global temperatures are definitely going to increase much faster (as a result of global warming incuded by extra greenhouse gases released by the USA as they now have no obligation to cut down on emissions), causing things such as more frequent extreme weather events (like hurricanes, due to the oceans being warmer, allowing more hurricanes to form over larger areas of the oceans which will be warm enough for hurricanes to form, over longer hurricane seasons, as well as droughts in areas further away from the oceans), sea levels rising (due to melting ice shelves), and generally screwing up the weather over the entire world.

These impacts will negatively affect the USA as well.

The areas around the east coast and the Gulf of Mexico are likely to be destroyed by a mixture of hurricanes and rising sea levels (you remember how New Orleans looked after getting hit by Hurrcane Katrina's storm surge? That, but permanent and all over the seaside areas of the USA), whilst the midwest will suffer rather large droughts and winds, making it just like how it was during the 1930s Dust Bowl, causing the USA's agriculture (production of crops, which is vital to ensuring that there is actually food for the USA) to be destroyed.

After this stuff, which, due to America's withdrawal from the Paris Climate Accords, will happen much sooner than if the USA stayed, the USA will be damaged beyond repair. By prioritizing short term economic benefits (any benefits from withdrawing from this) before long term economic benefits (the benefits provided by having simple things like having agriculture, decent weather, not having entire cities uninhabitable due to permanent sea-level rises, etc.), your president has fucked over your country.

But he probably doesn't care. He's old, and he knows that he's probably going to die of old age shortly after (or before) he gets impeached/loses the 2020 election/reaches the end of his 2nd term in 2024, so he doesn't give a single shit what will happen 10 years from now.

However, as you are probably going to be alive 10 years from now, you are going to suffer the consequences of this decision. Everyone is going to suffer the consequences of this decision.
For me, as someone who does not live in the USA (like most of the world), this is rather bad.

Why doesn't everyone just leave their fridge door open to cool the earth?

Because leaving your refrigerator door open will heat up your kitchen.  The condenser on the back of the appliance rejects an an amount of heat equal to the heat absorbed from the evaporator inside the unit, plus the mechanical work required to operate the compressor.  On net, the refrigerator generates heat.  You have to place the condenser external to the system you are trying to cool, if you want to cool the system.  That is what we do with air conditioning, by placing the condensers outdoors.  You would have to place the condenser in outer space, if you wanted to cool the planet with a refrigeration system.

I voted for McCain the first time, but by the second election Obama had won me over with his accomplishments and his attitude.¬† As a fiscal conservative, I was impressed with his goals of controlling the deficits, at the time of a recession, that wasn't politically easy or popular in his own party.¬† And yet he managed to improve the economy, halving unemployment, while still cutting the deficit by three-quarters.¬† Now it wasn't solely his doing, he listened to the economic experts at the time and signed an aggressive fiscal stimulus plan that really boosted the economy, while also tackling spending as much as feasible in the worst recession since the Great Depression.¬† People tend to forget that GDP had fallen to -8%¬†by the time he took office, and yet by 2010, it had jumped to +3.9% before moderating to a more stable 2.2%. It's a nearly unprecedented economic feat.¬† Sure, overall debt rose, but that's to be expected with a massive revenue hole left over before his term and you quickly saw deficits decline as he closed those holes. 

I could probably go on and on about the economic policies that I liked, especially the tax subsidies for R&D and education, which focused on long-term economic growth rather than short-term gains.¬† I also liked his reforms to reduce government waste, and his EO requiring CBA's to be submitted for nearly every major government policy and the results to be available to the public. There was a lot more transparency after that, and a lot of inefficiencies were fixed and waste eliminated (I've seen estimates of more than $3 billion in savings).¬† 

As for Obamacare, it's not ideal, but it's definitely better than what we had before.¬† As proof, medical bankruptcies are now half the rate they used to be.¬† Medical health cost inflation was halved as well. Some saw premiums go up, but for the vast majority, those premium increases were absorbed by subsidies.¬† And overall, costs are much lower for those who need it the most, i.e. the elderly, the disabled, and those with pre-existing conditions. 

I know this will get some flack from my friends on the left, but I don't actually agree with free healthcare (I think that the healthcare industry in the US would require huge reforms before it would be feasible and I don't see it happening).¬† I think the ACA would work a lot better with just a few substantial tweaks.¬† 

Now, Obama wasn't perfect.¬† For example, he failed to double manufacturing as promised... but in his defence, he increased it by a record amount, over 40% when manufacturing jobs had been declining for decades.¬†¬†But he didn't panic when many presidents would have, when faced with the same challenges.¬† He made a lot of right moves early on.¬† And he did it with aplomb, maintaining a ready wit and a graciousness to his detractors.¬† When the media reported something negative about him, he would reply, "I don't always like what they say, but I'll defend their right to say it."¬† That kind of attitude seems very impressive these days in comparison.

+mitch paul¬† The study authors admit that they didn't perform a full cost-benefit analysis (read their¬†press release¬†linked below).¬† The study looked at costs only and not the net benefit.¬† However even their costs were wildly exaggerated based on certain unrealistic assumptions.¬† 

1.¬† Again, they didn't look at the amount of jobs that would be created by following the Paris Agreement, which would require a substantial boost in new infrastructure building and investment in R&D.¬† Renewables generally produce two to three times more jobs (using¬†conservative estimates) than¬†fossil fuel jobs.

2. The NERA study ignores that in real world studies and historically, increases in energy efficiency (as would result via the Paris Agreement) generates net savings for consumers.¬† As an example, while increased fuel efficiency standards may cost auto-manufacturers millions to implement, they generate billions in cost savings to consumers in the form of reduced fuel costs.¬† In the NERA study, increased efficiency is shown up as a net cost, when it should show up as a net benefit. 

3. The study did not account for the enormous costs of pollution and climate change.¬† While numbers vary, the IPCC suggests figures as high as 10% of global GDP.¬† The climate sceptic Cato Institute points out that economic losses caused by climate change primarily affects third-world nations in tropical regions¬†and¬†that¬†the USA should only experience a 1% drag on GDP.¬† Even taking Cato's numbers, a 1% loss of GDP per year is effectively higher than the costs of implementing the Paris Agreement.¬† Taking into effect health benefits from reducing emissions (which include more than CO2), then the net benefits are much higher.¬† 

4.¬†The figures as quoted from the study came from one of the more extreme scenarios, assuming that companies and countries would choose the most expensive options in order to meet Paris Agreement goals.¬† This is highly unrealistic, as most companies would choose the cheapest option, not the most expensive. This core scenario also assumes a 40% reduction in emissions in the industrial sector- which is not stated in the Paris Agreement- which grossly overstates the changes in outputs and jobs.¬† Out of four scenarios, why do media pundits pick the most extreme one?¬† The more realistic scenarios look at companies choosing the cheapest, most flexible options to meet reduction targets, which (not surprisingly) shows vastly lower costs and job losses. 

5. The NERA study does not account for innovation or technology change, assuming that costs remain flat and that the price of renewables will not fall.¬† This is extremely unrealistic and skews the projection; as an example, the price of solar has fallen by about 40% every 5-6 years (and 12% in the last year alone).¬† The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory is predicting another 18% drop in costs in the next two years, with a further decrease expected every year after that. Yet the NERA study assumes that the price of¬†renewables remains¬†constant for the next 8 years.¬† 

6. Historically, in the past ten years we have reduced emissions by around 14% with no statistically discernable job losses or economic¬†loss.¬† It's unrealistic to believe that meeting a 26% reduction goal would have such potent negative effects when a 14% reduction had virtually no effect.¬† Especially as the Paris Agreement gave us the flexibility to meet our targets via any method we wished.¬† In addition, a study of the 9 states in the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative over the past 6 years showed a nearly 33% reduction in CO2, creating a net savings for consumers on their power bills of about $1.5 billion, creating a net of 22,000 jobs, and bringing net¬†economic benefits worth about $2.9 billion.¬† These states showed an exact opposite of NERA's predictions and they had higher emission caps than the ones proposed in the Paris Agreement.¬† In general, the NERA study does not account for past data.¬† http://www.nera.com/news-events/press-releases/2017/nera-economic-consultings-study-of-us-emissions-reduction-polici.html

1. Under the accord, the U.S. had a target of reducing its carbon emissions to 26-28% below 2005 levels by 2025. That alone would have resulted in "extreme changes in energy use" because "even Mr. Obama‚Äôs bevy of anti-carbon regulations would get the U.S. to a mere 45% of its target," per The Wall Street Journal editorial board.

2. The accord would have required the countries involved to raise their carbon emission-cutting goals every five years. The Obama administration intended to eventually curb carbon emissions by 80%, essentially North Korea levels.

3. The accord is non-binding legally, but activist courts may have used it as a legal weapon. 

4. The accord doesn't hold China and India to a high standard. 
China and India offered benchmarks pegged to GDP growth, which means they can continue their current energy plans. China won‚Äôt even begin reducing emissions until 2030 and in the next five years it will use more coal. 

China also can't be trusted to reduce their carbon emissions since they have a history of misrepresenting their total emission levels.

5. The U.S. had pledged $3 billion a year to the United Nations' Green Climate Fund. Under the accord, participants would provide $100 billion to organizations like the Green Climate Fund to provide money to poorer countries to neutralize the costs of curtailing carbon emissions. The Obama administration has already funneled $1 billion to the organization without congressional approval as part of a $3 billion pledge.

While it's true that China is the top emitter of carbon dioxide, they also represent over 18% of the world's population. If you look at the per capita numbers they're at the middle of the pack - with less than half of the emissions per capita of the US.

What can be said is that they've been having a rather extreme upward trend in the last few decades, unlike most western nations, and far more steep in it's rise than a nation of comparable population such as India. I'd also be very careful about believing claims of Chinese emissions having peaked (it's been predicted before and been untrue), as economic factors are likely a far larger part of the story than altruism. Best case scenario would be them hitting a plateau, but it's unlikely that we'll see any drop-off soon. If the Chinese economy gets an upswing and more people aquire wealth (after all, despite the per capita numbers being important, a far smaller percentage of the Chinese population are responsible for the country's emissions than in western nations) it's unlikely that emissions will decrease, and even possible that they will increase.

However, being allowed to increase emissions is not the same as increasing emissions. Suggesting that the Paris agreement is worthless because of hypotheticals treating the agreement as though it existed in a vacuum is disingenuous. It's a part of a global effort. It's not THE global effort.

Honestly. It's not that hard to try to see the issue from a few different perspectives.

What is the cause of climate change and how can it be solved?
Many people think that the cause of climate change is carbon dioxide, and reducing carbon dioxide can prevent climate change.
This is a bit convincing, but not correct.
The exact cause of climate change is "thermal excess" on the earth.
Therefore, to stop climate change, we must focus on stopping of the "thermal excess".

"GREEN NEW DEAL" has good intentions. However, there are several problems. 
The biggest problem is that it is less economical. It means that it is difficult for many people to actively participate. 
Therefore, coercion must be mobilized to achieve the desired goal, and excessive coercion hinders the achievement of the goal. 
This is a fundamental problem.
Also, waste is another problem. 
Waste solar cells and waste blades are discharged, and the waste batteries of ESS adversely affect the environment.

Although there is a problem with the need for large land, the best way to reduce heat and carbon dioxide is to create big forests.
Trump should publicize the effects of "One trillion trees" to others and urge the world to join in and work together.

Why is "One trillion trees" so effective?
First of all, it is economical. Compared to solar power generation and wind power generation, it does not require a lot of funds at the beginning. 
forests has a long lifespan, and does not require additional facilities such as ESS and power transmission and distribution facilities, and does not emit waste.

In addition, One trillion trees absorb enormous amounts of solar heat.
Photosynthesis requires infrared rays from the sun.
It absorbs infrared rays (heat rays) and ultraviolet rays to perform photosynthesis, turning carbon dioxide into oxygen and making glucose.
One trillion trees absorbing solar heat is very good at slowing down climate change. 
The reason people don't really care about trees absorbing heat is that they don't think the cause of global warming is fundamentally "overheating," but rather carbon dioxide.

The video implies that man's CO2 gas is the thermostat by which Earth's temperature can be modulated. This is false because, first, 95 percent of the greenhouse gas effect in Earth's atmosphere is caused by water vapor. 1/3rd of the remaining 5 percent is CO2 gas. 3 percent of this is man's total contribution since 1850 accounting for an estimated 0.1 percent of the greenhouse gas effect.

Second, 95 percent of the narrow band of infrared radiation available for CO2 to emmit is doing so already. So doubling CO2 would make no measurable difference.

Third, changes in the appearance of atmospheric CO2 gas occur at least 800 years AFTER changes in temperature. CO2 is an effect, not a cause.

Since the peak of the Little Ice Age 350 years ago, the global mean surface temperature has been rising at a rate of 0.8C/century and, to this day, hasn't deviated by more than 1.5 percent from the mean.

Conclusion: Be happy in a world where warm is good and cold bad.

That's incorrect, climate naturally gets either warmer or colder. Here you can see the natural global warming from the last glacial maximum (20000 to 10000 years ago) and the slow natural cooling that happened during most of human civilization: http://railsback.org/FQS/FQS22katoFutureTemps03.jpg
That up-tick at the very end is the warming we have caused during the last century (including a projection till 2100), and it's clearly unnaturally fast. And it's the speed of climate change that worries scientists, because that's what makes it so hard for humans and nature to adapt.
According to the vast majority of climate experts, the only reasonable cause for this recent warming is the drastic increase of atmospheric greenhouse gas concentration that happened over the same period of time. Other causes such as changes in ocean currents, solar activity or cosmic rays have been considered thoroughly, and they simply don't correlate with the recent rise in global temperature and can therefore be excluded as the main cause. CO2 concentration on the other hand does correlate well both over the last century *and* over hundreds of thousand of years.

@Oldinea Miller Your mathematics is wrong and let me explain why it is so using an analogy:

Assume I am driving car for 10 hours continuously without any break with different speed. So first 7 hours, I drive at varying speeds not exceeding 50 miles/hr and then in last 3 hours, I increase my speed by 1.5 times after each hour. 
So, assume I am at 50 miles/hr at end of 7 hours. So after eighth hour, I am at (50*1.5=75 miles/hr) and after ninth hour, I am at (75*1.5=112.5 miles/hr) and finally at the end of tenth hour, my speed is (112.5*1.5=168.75 miles/hr).

So as per your logic, I will say my increase in speed per hour was: (168.75 - 0.0)/10 = 16.875 miles/hour. BUT THAT IS WRONG.

In reality, I was slow and did not exceed 50 miles/hr for first 7 hours and then I ACCELERATED ONLY IN LAST 3 HOURS. 

So my average increase in speed per hour WILL GIVE ME FALSE IMPRESSION THAT I DID NOT ACCELERATE IN THE END AND 16.875 miles/hr is pretty decent increase in speed for 10 hour journey.

I accept that climate change is happening and that humans are strongly contributing to it. I am a strong advocate for lowering pollution of all kinds, immediately switching to sustainable industry methods (agriculture, fishing etc), and phasing out fossil fuels as quickly as can be reasonably achieved without destroying economies,  especially those of developing countries. But as a data scientist, I cannot stand the utter fetishization of predictive models in the climate change debate. Models of such complex systems are simply not accurate on those timescales. The idea that we can reliably predict to the tenth of a degree what the temperature will be in 100 years, using the current models, is simply false. The idea that we can precisely predict how large of an effect a specific policy will have over 100 years, is simply false. I am not saying the models are completely wrong or that they are not useful. They are useful and they should be used. But you MUST present the uncertainly analysis along with them. Anything else is scientific malpractice.

I think you missed the point of the video. The point is to be rallying cry to tell people that more needs to be done. All models are wrong, but some are useful. In this case the models being used are useful because they can perhaps convince the public of the importance of climate change so that they vote for a candidate who will do better and speak out against the corporations controlling and manipulating the government. This video isn't a scientific paper that aims to predict anything. It is just saying that we aren't doing enough. People are going to see this video and tell their friends and families that we aren't doing enough about climate change, they aren't going to use this as a source in this scientific paper or memorize the numbers said to tell everyone.

@NatGazer Funnily enough, governments all around the world are throwing money around like it's going out of fashion on furlough and other measures to protect small businesses, so I'm not sure that corona is the best comparison.

With regard to climate change, I don't really see why small businesses would be hit harder than big businesses because any tax levied would presumably scale with turnover, and the big businesses would therefore pay more. Let's say you have two haulage firms, A and B. A has ten times as many lorries as B, it has ten times the turnover and makes ten times the profit. Its lorry fleet covers ten times the distance of B's, so it's also using ten times as much carbon as B, and it would have to pay ten times as much in carbon taxes - the same proportion of its profits. I don't see how B is hit worse by this kind of thing than A.

That's just a result of this map projection. It's impossible to map the surface of a globe to a 2D plane without experiencing some form of warping, stretching, or other changes to size, shape, or distance. So, there are many different map projections, that all have their pros and cons. This appears to be the Mercator projection, and is one of the most common projections used. It accurately portrays shape (mostly, there are certain exceptions) and distance, but stretches the size of landmasses the further away from the equator they are. That's why North America appears enormous, even though in reality its relatively comparable to Africa in size.

Now about *why* ? Its just basic chemistry. The molecules of greenhouse gases have very good heat trapping capabilities. G.g. molecules can absorb energy from infrared (IR) radiations, basically photons(packets of energy) & energy from the photon causes the CO2¬†molecule to vibrate. Some time later, the molecule gives up this extra energy by emitting another infrared photon. Once the extra energy has been removed by the emitted photon, the carbon dioxide molecule stops vibrating. Molecules are constantly in motion, colliding with other gas molecules and transferring energy from one molecule to another during collisions. In the more-complex, real-world process, a¬†CO2¬†molecule would most likely bump into several other gas molecules before re-emitting the infrared photon. The¬†CO2¬†molecule might transfer the energy it gained from the absorbed photon to another molecule, adding speed to that molecule's motion. Since the temperature of a gas is a measure of the speed of the molecules in the gas, the faster motion of a molecule that eventually results from the IR photon that was absorbed by a¬†CO2¬†molecule raises the temperature of the gases in the atmosphere.

This ability to absorb and re-emit infrared energy is what makes CO2¬†an effective heat-trapping greenhouse gas. Not all gas molecules are able to absorb IR radiation. For example,¬†nitrogen¬†(N2) and¬†oxygen¬†(O2), which make up more than 90% of Earth's atmosphere, do not absorb infrared photons. CO2¬†molecules¬†can vibrate in ways¬†that simpler nitrogen and oxygen molecules cannot, which allows CO2¬†molecules to capture the IR photons. Greenhouse gases and the¬†greenhouse effect¬†play an important role in Earth's climate. Without greenhouse gases, our planet would be a¬†frozen ball of ice. In recent years, however, excess emissions of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases from human activities (mostly burning fossil fuels) have begun to warm Earth's climate at a problematic rate. Other significant greenhouse gases include water vapor (H2O),¬†methane¬†(CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O) and¬†ozone¬†(O3).

I think with so many people digging in their heels as to which "side" they're on, it's important to note first that nothing can be remedied unless we're both willing to look at both sides of the issue and consider deep within ourselves only the facts objectively, away from all the noise.

What I seem to understand at this time is simply this: the majority left says that the vast majority of scientists on the topic will agree that the climate is changing.  

-The right will contend hence that science is not a popularity vote (and that big money government backing only affords those who agree with their beliefs on Climate Change, thus creating a foundation of bias in the scientific community - very unscientific indeed) with the added statement that THEY TOO agree the climate is changing in that CO2 is rising, making the globe warmer, but that it was happening long before man came on the scene with the Industrial Revolution and since.  They will also add that we simply don't know whether there is a significant correlation between the wrongs man has done and the kinds of affects that we associate with CO2 rising.  

-From what I can gather the left will then perhaps try to make the claim that it doesn't matter right now if we know these things or not; let's play it safe and do all we can now before we face possible appocolyptic catastrophes by making stringent regulations on the major things we know contribute to increased CO2 levels.  

-The right responds with the rationale of we don't know if our basis for these propositions is even correct, so why spend so much money and time on what we know can only at best change the global environment over the course of a hundred years to an infinitesimal degree.  One so small it would have no real effect on the things we care about for why we are doing this to begin with, and with that - at a cost that could have potentially been spent on needs that we both DID KNOW were real issues AND could have an enormous positive effect to the degree we all would hope for.  

With all this the right again would like to add that CO2 happens to be what essentially all plants around the world breath.  Therefore, how could this be as harmful as they say. Given the knowledge gained from paleoclimatic studies, several explanations for the ongoing warming trend can be eliminated. Changes in Earth‚Äôs tectonism and its orbit are far too slow to have played a significant role in the observed rate of temperature increase over the last 150 years. At the other extreme, large volcanic eruptions have cooled global climate for a year or two, and El Ni√±o episodes have warmed it for about a year, but neither factor dominates longer-term trends. Extensive efforts to find any other natural explanation for the recent trend have similarly failed.

As a result, greenhouse-gas concentrations and solar output are the principal remaining factors that could have changed rapidly enough and lasted long enough to explain the observed changes in global temperature. The 5th IPCC report (2013) concluded that solar irradiance changes contributed only a few percent to changes in radiative forcing of the atmosphere over the past century. Throughout the era of satellite observation, during periods of strong warming, the data show little evidence of increased solar influence (Foster and Rahmstorf, 2011; Lean and Rind, 2008).

Greenhouse gas concentrations remain the major explanation for the warming. Observations and climate model assessments of the natural and anthropogenic factors responsible for this warming conclude that rising anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases have been an increasingly important contributor since the mid-1800s and the major factor since the mid-1900s (Meehl et al., 2004). The CO2 concentration in the atmosphere is now ~40% higher than peak levels measured in ice cores spanning 800,000 years of age, and the methane concentration is 1.5 times higher (IPCC, 2013). The measured increases in greenhouse gases are more than enough to explain the observed global temperature increase at Earth‚Äôs surface. In fact, considered in isolation, the greenhouse gas increases during the last 150 years would have caused a warming larger than that actually measured, but mechanisms that limit increases in near-surface air temperatures from aerosols, ocean heat storage, and possibly clouds have offset part of the warming. In addition, because the oceans take decades to centuries to respond fully to climatic forcing, the climate system has yet to register the full effect of recent greenhouse gas increases.  https://www.geosociety.org/gsa/positions/position10.aspx

Mike Bonnell let me propose that the reason scientists don‚Äôt answer the ‚Äòperfect‚Äô temperature question is because they simply have no idea how the climate will operate when you change one or two parameters. There was an interesting study after the 2012 storm in New York detailing how much worse the storm would have been if you raised sea surface temperature 2C. I think the science was perfectly reasonable theoretical science, the problem with it was that it never modeled the exact meteorological conditions that we would experience in that scenario. Why? Because it simply isn‚Äôt possible. The result is we know some cool things, but we didn‚Äôt learn anything of real value.

The basic claim, that the so-called 97 percent of scientists believe, is that a very small increase in energy conservation causes by elevated levels of CO2 is a very believable claim. That increased level of temperature increases the level of water vapor in the air which has a much greater effect on warming than CO2. So far so good.

The alarmists basically argue that water vapor feedback is the cause of runaway, one directional warming.

My contention is that, that almost certainly cannot be true. If that were the case, an extraordinary active sunspot cycle, particularly combined with the Milankovitch cycle, combined with volcanic activity, would easily produce a short term global temperature increase that would have triggered this water vapor feedback.

Another fun anomaly; Mt Tambora volcano in 1814 caused the ‚Äòyear without a summer‚Äô across North America and Europe. It is estimated that the energy blocking effect of the aerosols from that eruption, lowered global temperature by about 3 degrees C. Yet the global temperature rather quickly recovered and things went back to normal.

If you stop the narrative at the water vapor feedback, it sounds like you might have a case. But the huge unknown is cloud formation. You do need water vapor for cloud formation. Even further complicating it, is the fact not all clouds are equal. Some clouds, particularly nighttime clouds have an even greater warming effect, however, daytime clouds often have enormous cooling effects. Reality tends to cut both ways,  normally you can safely discount voices that claim the evidence is all one way.

In 1988, James Hansen warned the nation about climate change.  By then, the CO2 concentration in the atmosphere, had already reached 350 ppm.  The global average temperature associated with that level of CO2 was already going to go beyond 4 degrees C above pre-industrial averages.  The only difference is it would have taken much longer to reach that level, as the ice would not have melted as quickly, giving many species time to adapt to the changing climate, and humans would have had a much better chance of finding tech to take CO2 out of the atmosphere.  Now above 410 ppm of CO2, the change is happening much too fast for any chance at adaptation or removal.
